# Framework Completion Criteria
## Brisart Research Archive  

This document defines the criteria under which a framework within the Brisart Research Archive is considered complete for public release. These criteria ensure structural consistency, empirical interpretability, and system-level compatibility across the archive.

Completion does not imply full operational disclosure. A framework may be complete at the public specification layer while retaining implementation-specific detail within the institutional layer.

---

## 1. Bounded Mechanism

A framework must define a clearly bounded mechanism.

This requires:

- A specific cognitive, perceptual, or interactional process  
- Explicit scope and domain of applicability  
- Defined separation from adjacent or overlapping mechanisms  

The mechanism must be interpretable as a self-contained system.

---

## 2. Explicit Component Structure

A framework must define its internal components.

Each component must:

- Represent a distinct functional role  
- Operate over identifiable inputs and outputs  
- Be structurally distinguishable from other components  

The framework must be expressible as a finite, closed set of interacting elements.

---

## 3. Formalized Dynamics

The relationships between components must be explicitly defined as a dynamic system.

This includes:

- Directional flow of information  
- Recursive or iterative update processes  
- Time-based or state-based transitions  

The system must describe how internal state evolves under defined conditions.

---

## 4. Formal Specification

Each framework must include at least one formal representation.

This may take the form of:

- Equations  
- Symbolic models  
- Threshold conditions  
- Weighted relations or transformation functions  

The formal specification must:

- Correspond directly to defined components  
- Avoid implicit or undefined processes  
- Support computational interpretation  

---

## 5. Constraint and Boundary Definition

Each framework must define its operational limitations.

This includes:

- Explicit scope conditions  
- Excluded phenomena  
- Assumptions required for validity  
- Conditions under which the mechanism fails or degrades  

A framework must define what it does not model as explicitly as what it does.

---

## 6. Emergent Behavior Characterization

The framework must describe system-level behavior arising from component interaction.

This includes:

- Stable patterns  
- Transitional states  
- Failure modes  
- Edge conditions  

Behavior must be described in terms that are:

- Observable  
- Measurable  
- Predictable under defined conditions  

---

## 7. Empirical Relevance

A complete framework must generate testable predictions.

This includes:

- Observable behavioral or system-level outcomes  
- Conditions under which predictions hold  
- Conditions under which predictions are falsified  

The framework must support empirical evaluation, even if full validation is not yet complete.

---

## 8. Integration Compatibility (Conceptual)

Each framework must be evaluable within the broader archive.

This requires:

- Defined input structures  
- Defined output structures  
- Compatibility with shared system-level constructs  

The framework must be capable of conceptual integration without requiring modification of its core mechanism.

---

## 9. Abstract Implementation Mapping

The framework must support translation into an implementation structure.

This includes:

- Mapping components to functional roles (e.g., modules or interfaces)  
- Defining input/output relationships  
- Supporting iterative or loop-based execution models  

This requirement ensures that:

> the framework can be operationalized without structural ambiguity.

Implementation-ready detail is not required at the public layer.

---

## 10. Structural Completeness

A framework is considered structurally complete when:

- No required components remain undefined  
- No necessary relationships remain implicit  
- All described behavior can be traced to defined components and dynamics  

Partial, speculative, or unbounded frameworks do not meet this criterion.

---

## 11. Archive Standardization

Each framework must conform to archive-wide structural standards.

This includes:

- Consistent section organization  
- Standardized terminology  
- Alignment with the Brisart Format  

This ensures interpretability across the archive as a unified system.

---

## 12. Public vs Institutional Sufficiency

A framework may be complete at the public specification level without including full operational detail.

Public completeness includes:

- Mechanism definition  
- Component structure  
- Dynamics and formal specification  
- Behavioral description  
- Abstract implementation mapping  

Institutional completeness includes:

- Parameterization  
- Calibration logic  
- Execution configuration  
- Integration tuning  

These elements are not required for public completion and are provided under institutional access.

---

## Completion Definition

A framework is considered complete when it satisfies all criteria defined in this document at the public specification level.

Frameworks that do not meet all criteria remain in development and are not considered part of the finalized archive.

---

## Functional Summary

Completion criteria within the Brisart Research Archive ensure that all released frameworks are:

- Mechanistically defined  
- Structurally explicit  
- Dynamically coherent  
- Formally specified  
- Empirically interpretable  
- Architecturally compatible  
- Implementation-ready at an abstract level  

These criteria maintain consistency across the archive while preserving separation between public specification and institutional operation.
